      body:
        "Three processes are often muddled up: **respiration**, **photosynthesis** and **breathing**. Keeping them straight is one of the most exam-tested skills in this topic.\n\n**Respiration vs photosynthesis** — in many ways they are opposites:\n\n- Respiration: glucose + oxygen → carbon dioxide + water (**releases** energy). Happens in **all** living cells, **all the time**.\n- Photosynthesis: carbon dioxide + water → glucose + oxygen (**stores** energy from light). Happens **only in green plant cells** with chlorophyll, **in the light**.\n- A green plant does **both**: in daylight it photosynthesises faster than it respires, but it still respires day and night.\n\n**Plants respire all the time.** It is worth stating clearly: a plant respires in **every one of its cells, day and night** — roots, stems, flowers and leaves alike. It does **not** only respire at night or 'when it is not photosynthesising'. During the day photosynthesis simply happens at the same time, and usually faster, which is why overall we see the plant taking in carbon dioxide — but the respiration underneath never stops.\n\n**Respiration vs breathing (ventilation):**\n\n- **Breathing/ventilation** is the muscular movement of air in and out of the lungs. It is **not** a chemical reaction.\n- **Respiration** is a chemical reaction in cells releasing energy.\n- Breathing **supplies** oxygen for aerobic respiration and removes the carbon dioxide it makes — they are linked, but not the same.",
